---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { getPost } from '../../data/posts';
import { engageHref, projects, withBase } from '../../site.config';

const post = getPost('vllm-hf-gpu-idle')!;
const siteOrigin = Astro.site?.origin ?? 'https://sollabs.tech';
const structuredData = [
  {
    '@type': 'BlogPosting',
    headline: post.title,
    datePublished: post.date,
    description: post.description,
    author: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'Sol Labs' },
    publisher: { '@id': `${siteOrigin}/#organization` },
  },
];
---

<Layout
  title={`${post.title} · Sol Labs`}
  description={post.description}
  current="blog"
  ogType="article"
  publishedTime={post.date}
  structuredData={structuredData}
>
  <article class="page-wrap">
    <div class="prose">
      <p class="meta">{post.date} · {post.icp}</p>
      <h1>{post.title}</h1>
      <p>
        On Kubernetes, “just pull from Hugging Face” is fine for a laptop. In CI matrices and vLLM
        replica fleets, it is a cost and availability control. The Hub is a dependency you do not
        operate — and GPUs do not pause their billing while weights crawl across the public internet.
      </p>

      <h2>Rate limits are a production event</h2>
      <p>
        Hugging Face publishes resolver and API quotas. Anonymous traffic is limited per IP; shared
        CI egress burns that budget quickly (
        <a href="https://huggingface.co/docs/hub/en/rate-limits">Hub rate limits</a>).
        Hugging Face’s own tokenizers CI caches fixtures and authenticates downloads for that reason
        (
        <a href="https://github.com/huggingface/tokenizers/commit/3ba8ad0061a885baf052bbb7bbd22857e73e0c4e"
          >tokenizers CI change</a
        >). Operators see 429s that look like hung downloads when clients sleep on <code>RateLimit</code>
        headers.
      </p>

      <h2>Idle GPU time is the bill you feel</h2>
      <p>
        Practitioner write-ups on GKE model caching show multi‑tens of minutes of cold pull for large
        weights, with accelerators billed while waiting. Even rough $/hour math on A100-class nodes
        makes ten restarts a week material — before counting duplicate egress across replicas (
        <a href="https://hrittikhere.com/posts/model-caching-kubernetes-gke">model caching on GKE</a>).
        Treat the number as directional until you measure your fleet; the mechanism is not.
      </p>

      <h2>Cache is an ops control</h2>
      <p>
        Authenticated tokens raise Hub quotas. They do not remove Hub as a scale-out SPOF. A
        pull-through cache with pre-warm and optional cached-only misses keeps warm hits on disk you
        control. The Pulsys case study measures that path and publishes the results on
        <a href={projects.pulsys.href}>pulsys.io</a>.
      </p>

      <h2>Pitch order that matches buyer pain</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>Dollars of idle GPU and egress avoided</li>
        <li>Hub reliability when you scale or recover nodes</li>
        <li>Token isolation and auth defaults</li>
        <li>Kernel warm-path performance (last)</li>
      </ol>

      <p>
        <a
          class="btn btn--primary"
          href={engageHref}
          data-analytics-event="primary_cta_click"
          data-analytics-prop-location="article_model_cache"
        >
          Let's Talk
        </a>
        {' '}
        <a class="btn btn--secondary" href={withBase('/services/ai-infrastructure/')}>AI Infrastructure</a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>
